5373 // DeoptimizationOutputData is a fixed array used to hold the deoptimization
5374 // data for code generated by the full compiler.
5375 // The format of the these objects is
5376 // [i * 2]: Ast ID for ith deoptimization.
5377 // [i * 2 + 1]: PC and state of ith deoptimization
5378 class DeoptimizationOutputData: public FixedArray {
5379  public:
5380  int DeoptPoints() { return length() / 2; }
5381 
5382  BailoutId AstId(int index) {
5383  return BailoutId(Smi::cast(get(index * 2))->value());
5384  }
5385 
5386  void SetAstId(int index, BailoutId id) {
5387  set(index * 2, Smi::FromInt(id.ToInt()));
5388  }
5389 
5390  Smi* PcAndState(int index) { return Smi::cast(get(1 + index * 2)); }
5391  void SetPcAndState(int index, Smi* offset) { set(1 + index * 2, offset); }
5392 
5393  static int LengthOfFixedArray(int deopt_points) {
5394  return deopt_points * 2;
5395  }
5396 
5397  // Allocates a DeoptimizationOutputData.
5398  static Handle<DeoptimizationOutputData> New(Isolate* isolate,
5399  int number_of_deopt_points,
5400  PretenureFlag pretenure);
5401 
5402  DECLARE_CAST(DeoptimizationOutputData)
5403 
5404 #if defined(OBJECT_PRINT) || defined(ENABLE_DISASSEMBLER)
5405  void DeoptimizationOutputDataPrint(OStream& os); // NOLINT
5406 #endif
5407 };

5684  // The entire code object including its header is copied verbatim to the
5685  // snapshot so that it can be written in one, fast, memcpy during
5686  // deserialization. The deserializer will overwrite some pointers, rather
5687  // like a runtime linker, but the random allocation addresses used in the
5688  // mksnapshot process would still be present in the unlinked snapshot data,
5689  // which would make snapshot production non-reproducible. This method wipes
5690  // out the to-be-overwritten header data for reproducible snapshots.

5885  PlatformSmiTagging::kSmiValueSize - 11 + 1> {}; // NOLINT

5887  // KindSpecificFlags1 layout (STUB and OPTIMIZED_FUNCTION)

5890  static const int kHasFunctionCacheBit =
5891  kStackSlotsFirstBit + kStackSlotsBitCount;
5892  static const int kMarkedForDeoptimizationBit = kHasFunctionCacheBit + 1;
5893  static const int kWeakStubBit = kMarkedForDeoptimizationBit + 1;
5894  static const int kInvalidatedWeakStubBit = kWeakStubBit + 1;
5895  static const int kIsTurbofannedBit = kInvalidatedWeakStubBit + 1;
5896 
5897  STATIC_ASSERT(kStackSlotsFirstBit + kStackSlotsBitCount <= 32);
5898  STATIC_ASSERT(kIsTurbofannedBit + 1 <= 32);
5899

5901  kStackSlotsFirstBit, kStackSlotsBitCount> {}; // NOLINT

5908  : public BitField<bool, kInvalidatedWeakStubBit, 1> {}; // NOLINT

5965 
5966 class CompilationInfo;
5967 
5968 // This class describes the layout of dependent codes array of a map. The
5969 // array is partitioned into several groups of dependent codes. Each group
5970 // contains codes with the same dependency on the map. The array has the
5971 // following layout for n dependency groups:
5972 //
5973 // +----+----+-----+----+---------+----------+-----+---------+-----------+
5974 // | C1 | C2 | ... | Cn | group 1 | group 2 | ... | group n | undefined |
5975 // +----+----+-----+----+---------+----------+-----+---------+-----------+
5976 //
5977 // The first n elements are Smis, each of them specifies the number of codes
5978 // in the corresponding group. The subsequent elements contain grouped code
5979 // objects. The suffix of the array can be filled with the undefined value if
5980 // the number of codes is less than the length of the array. The order of the
5981 // code objects within a group is not preserved.
5982 //
5983 // All code indexes used in the class are counted starting from the first
5984 // code object of the first group. In other words, code index 0 corresponds
5985 // to array index n = kCodesStartIndex.
5986 
5987 class DependentCode: public FixedArray {
5988  public:
5989  enum DependencyGroup {
5990  // Group of IC stubs that weakly embed this map and depend on being
5991  // invalidated when the map is garbage collected. Dependent IC stubs form
5992  // a linked list. This group stores only the head of the list. This means
5993  // that the number_of_entries(kWeakICGroup) is 0 or 1.
5994  kWeakICGroup,
5995  // Group of code that weakly embed this map and depend on being
5996  // deoptimized when the map is garbage collected.
5997  kWeakCodeGroup,
5998  // Group of code that embed a transition to this map, and depend on being
5999  // deoptimized when the transition is replaced by a new version.
6000  kTransitionGroup,
6001  // Group of code that omit run-time prototype checks for prototypes
6002  // described by this map. The group is deoptimized whenever an object
6003  // described by this map changes shape (and transitions to a new map),
6004  // possibly invalidating the assumptions embedded in the code.
6005  kPrototypeCheckGroup,
6006  // Group of code that depends on elements not being added to objects with
6007  // this map.
6008  kElementsCantBeAddedGroup,
6009  // Group of code that depends on global property values in property cells
6010  // not being changed.
6011  kPropertyCellChangedGroup,
6012  // Group of code that omit run-time type checks for the field(s) introduced
6013  // by this map.
6014  kFieldTypeGroup,
6015  // Group of code that omit run-time type checks for initial maps of
6016  // constructors.
6017  kInitialMapChangedGroup,
6018  // Group of code that depends on tenuring information in AllocationSites
6019  // not being changed.
6020  kAllocationSiteTenuringChangedGroup,
6021  // Group of code that depends on element transition information in
6022  // AllocationSites not being changed.
6023  kAllocationSiteTransitionChangedGroup,
6024  kGroupCount = kAllocationSiteTransitionChangedGroup + 1
6025  };
6026 
6027  // Array for holding the index of the first code object of each group.
6028  // The last element stores the total number of code objects.
6029  class GroupStartIndexes {
6030  public:
6031  explicit GroupStartIndexes(DependentCode* entries);
6032  void Recompute(DependentCode* entries);
6033  int at(int i) { return start_indexes_[i]; }
6034  int number_of_entries() { return start_indexes_[kGroupCount]; }
6035  private:
6036  int start_indexes_[kGroupCount + 1];
6037  };
6038 
6039  bool Contains(DependencyGroup group, Code* code);
6040  static Handle<DependentCode> Insert(Handle<DependentCode> entries,
6041  DependencyGroup group,
6042  Handle<Object> object);
6043  void UpdateToFinishedCode(DependencyGroup group,
6044  CompilationInfo* info,
6045  Code* code);
6046  void RemoveCompilationInfo(DependentCode::DependencyGroup group,
6047  CompilationInfo* info);
6048 
6049  void DeoptimizeDependentCodeGroup(Isolate* isolate,
6050  DependentCode::DependencyGroup group);
6051 
6052  bool MarkCodeForDeoptimization(Isolate* isolate,
6053  DependentCode::DependencyGroup group);
6054  void AddToDependentICList(Handle<Code> stub);
6055 
6056  // The following low-level accessors should only be used by this class
6057  // and the mark compact collector.
6058  inline int number_of_entries(DependencyGroup group);
6059  inline void set_number_of_entries(DependencyGroup group, int value);
6060  inline bool is_code_at(int i);
6061  inline Code* code_at(int i);
6062  inline CompilationInfo* compilation_info_at(int i);
6063  inline void set_object_at(int i, Object* object);
6064  inline Object** slot_at(int i);
6065  inline Object* object_at(int i);
6066  inline void clear_at(int i);
6067  inline void copy(int from, int to);
6068  DECLARE_CAST(DependentCode)
6069 
6070  static DependentCode* ForObject(Handle<HeapObject> object,
6071  DependencyGroup group);
6072 
6073  private:
6074  // Make a room at the end of the given group by moving out the first
6075  // code objects of the subsequent groups.
6076  inline void ExtendGroup(DependencyGroup group);
6077  static const int kCodesStartIndex = kGroupCount;
6078 };

6081 // All heap objects have a Map that describes their structure.
6082 // A Map contains information about:
6083 // - Size information about the object
6084 // - How to iterate over an object (for garbage collection)
6085 class Map: public HeapObject {
6086  public:
6087  // Instance size.
6088  // Size in bytes or kVariableSizeSentinel if instances do not have
6089  // a fixed size.
6090  inline int instance_size();
6091  inline void set_instance_size(int value);
6092 
6093  // Count of properties allocated in the object.
6094  inline int inobject_properties();
6095  inline void set_inobject_properties(int value);
6096 
6097  // Count of property fields pre-allocated in the object when first allocated.
6098  inline int pre_allocated_property_fields();
6099  inline void set_pre_allocated_property_fields(int value);
6100 
6101  // Instance type.
6102  inline InstanceType instance_type();
6103  inline void set_instance_type(InstanceType value);
6104 
6105  // Tells how many unused property fields are available in the
6106  // instance (only used for JSObject in fast mode).
6107  inline int unused_property_fields();
6108  inline void set_unused_property_fields(int value);
6109 
6110  // Bit field.
6111  inline byte bit_field();
6112  inline void set_bit_field(byte value);
6113 
6114  // Bit field 2.
6115  inline byte bit_field2();
6116  inline void set_bit_field2(byte value);
6117 
6118  // Bit field 3.
6119  inline uint32_t bit_field3();
6120  inline void set_bit_field3(uint32_t bits);
6121 
6122  class EnumLengthBits: public BitField<int,
6123  0, kDescriptorIndexBitCount> {}; // NOLINT
6124  class NumberOfOwnDescriptorsBits: public BitField<int,
6125  kDescriptorIndexBitCount, kDescriptorIndexBitCount> {}; // NOLINT
6126  STATIC_ASSERT(kDescriptorIndexBitCount + kDescriptorIndexBitCount == 20);
6127  class DictionaryMap : public BitField<bool, 20, 1> {};
6128  class OwnsDescriptors : public BitField<bool, 21, 1> {};
6129  class HasInstanceCallHandler : public BitField<bool, 22, 1> {};
6130  class Deprecated : public BitField<bool, 23, 1> {};
6131  class IsFrozen : public BitField<bool, 24, 1> {};
6132  class IsUnstable : public BitField<bool, 25, 1> {};
6133  class IsMigrationTarget : public BitField<bool, 26, 1> {};
6134  class DoneInobjectSlackTracking : public BitField<bool, 27, 1> {};
6135  // Bit 28 is free.
6136 
6137  // Keep this bit field at the very end for better code in
6138  // Builtins::kJSConstructStubGeneric stub.
6139  class ConstructionCount: public BitField<int, 29, 3> {};
6140 
6141  // Tells whether the object in the prototype property will be used
6142  // for instances created from this function. If the prototype
6143  // property is set to a value that is not a JSObject, the prototype
6144  // property will not be used to create instances of the function.
6145  // See ECMA-262, 13.2.2.
6146  inline void set_non_instance_prototype(bool value);
6147  inline bool has_non_instance_prototype();
6148 
6149  // Tells whether function has special prototype property. If not, prototype
6150  // property will not be created when accessed (will return undefined),
6151  // and construction from this function will not be allowed.
6152  inline void set_function_with_prototype(bool value);
6153  inline bool function_with_prototype();
6154 
6155  // Tells whether the instance with this map should be ignored by the
6156  // Object.getPrototypeOf() function and the __proto__ accessor.
6157  inline void set_is_hidden_prototype() {
6158  set_bit_field(bit_field() | (1 << kIsHiddenPrototype));
6159  }
6160 
6161  inline bool is_hidden_prototype() {
6162  return ((1 << kIsHiddenPrototype) & bit_field()) != 0;
6163  }
6164 
6165  // Records and queries whether the instance has a named interceptor.
6166  inline void set_has_named_interceptor() {
6167  set_bit_field(bit_field() | (1 << kHasNamedInterceptor));
6168  }
6169 
6170  inline bool has_named_interceptor() {
6171  return ((1 << kHasNamedInterceptor) & bit_field()) != 0;
6172  }
6173 
6174  // Records and queries whether the instance has an indexed interceptor.
6175  inline void set_has_indexed_interceptor() {
6176  set_bit_field(bit_field() | (1 << kHasIndexedInterceptor));
6177  }
6178 
6179  inline bool has_indexed_interceptor() {
6180  return ((1 << kHasIndexedInterceptor) & bit_field()) != 0;
6181  }
6182 
6183  // Tells whether the instance is undetectable.
6184  // An undetectable object is a special class of JSObject: 'typeof' operator
6185  // returns undefined, ToBoolean returns false. Otherwise it behaves like
6186  // a normal JS object. It is useful for implementing undetectable
6187  // document.all in Firefox & Safari.
6188  // See https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=248549.
6189  inline void set_is_undetectable() {
6190  set_bit_field(bit_field() | (1 << kIsUndetectable));
6191  }
6192 
6193  inline bool is_undetectable() {
6194  return ((1 << kIsUndetectable) & bit_field()) != 0;
6195  }
6196 
6197  // Tells whether the instance has a call-as-function handler.

6199  set_bit_field(bit_field() | (1 << kIsObserved));
6200  }
6201 
6202  inline bool is_observed() {
6203  return ((1 << kIsObserved) & bit_field()) != 0;
6204  }

6378  // [prototype transitions]: cache of prototype transitions.
6379  // Prototype transition is a transition that happens
6380  // when we change object's prototype to a new one.
6381  // Cache format:
6382  // 0: finger - index of the first free cell in the cache
6383  // 1: back pointer that overlaps with prototype transitions field.
6384  // 2 + 2 * i: prototype
6385  // 3 + 2 * i: target map
6386  inline FixedArray* GetPrototypeTransitions();

6389  static const int kProtoTransitionHeaderSize = 1;
6390  static const int kProtoTransitionNumberOfEntriesOffset = 0;
6391  static const int kProtoTransitionElementsPerEntry = 2;
6392  static const int kProtoTransitionPrototypeOffset = 0;
6393  static const int kProtoTransitionMapOffset = 1;
6394 
6395  inline int NumberOfProtoTransitions() {
6396  FixedArray* cache = GetPrototypeTransitions();
6397  if (cache->length() == 0) return 0;
6398  return
6399  Smi::cast(cache->get(kProtoTransitionNumberOfEntriesOffset))->value();
6400  }
6401 
6402  inline void SetNumberOfProtoTransitions(int value) {
6403  FixedArray* cache = GetPrototypeTransitions();
6404  DCHECK(cache->length() != 0);
6405  cache->set(kProtoTransitionNumberOfEntriesOffset, Smi::FromInt(value));
6406  }

6603  bool CanTransition() {

6606  return instance_type() >= FIRST_JS_OBJECT_TYPE;
6607  }

6609  bool IsJSObjectMap() {
6610  return instance_type() >= FIRST_JS_OBJECT_TYPE;
6611  }
6612  bool IsJSProxyMap() {
6613  InstanceType type = instance_type();
6614  return FIRST_JS_PROXY_TYPE <= type && type <= LAST_JS_PROXY_TYPE;
6615  }
6616  bool IsJSGlobalProxyMap() {
6617  return instance_type() == JS_GLOBAL_PROXY_TYPE;
6618  }
6619  bool IsJSGlobalObjectMap() {
6620  return instance_type() == JS_GLOBAL_OBJECT_TYPE;
6621  }
6622  bool IsGlobalObjectMap() {
6623  const InstanceType type = instance_type();
6624  return type == JS_GLOBAL_OBJECT_TYPE || type == JS_BUILTINS_OBJECT_TYPE;
6625  }

6657  // When you set the prototype of an object using the __proto__ accessor you
6658  // need a new map for the object (the prototype is stored in the map). In
6659  // order not to multiply maps unnecessarily we store these as transitions in
6660  // the original map. That way we can transition to the same map if the same
6661  // prototype is set, rather than creating a new map every time. The
6662  // transitions are in the form of a map where the keys are prototype objects
6663  // and the values are the maps the are transitioned to.
6664  static const int kMaxCachedPrototypeTransitions = 256;
6665  static Handle<Map> TransitionToPrototype(Handle<Map> map,
6666  Handle<Object> prototype);

7017 // List of builtin functions we want to identify to improve code
7018 // generation.
7019 //
7020 // Each entry has a name of a global object property holding an object
7021 // optionally followed by ".prototype", a name of a builtin function
7022 // on the object (the one the id is set for), and a label.
7023 //
7024 // Installation of ids for the selected builtin functions is handled
7025 // by the bootstrapper.
7026 #define FUNCTIONS_WITH_ID_LIST(V) \
7027  V(Array.prototype, indexOf, ArrayIndexOf) \
7028  V(Array.prototype, lastIndexOf, ArrayLastIndexOf) \
7029  V(Array.prototype, push, ArrayPush) \
7030  V(Array.prototype, pop, ArrayPop) \
7031  V(Array.prototype, shift, ArrayShift) \
7032  V(Function.prototype, apply, FunctionApply) \
7033  V(String.prototype, charCodeAt, StringCharCodeAt) \
7034  V(String.prototype, charAt, StringCharAt) \
7035  V(String, fromCharCode, StringFromCharCode) \
7036  V(Math, floor, MathFloor) \
7037  V(Math, round, MathRound) \
7038  V(Math, ceil, MathCeil) \
7039  V(Math, abs, MathAbs) \
7040  V(Math, log, MathLog) \
7041  V(Math, exp, MathExp) \
7042  V(Math, sqrt, MathSqrt) \
7043  V(Math, pow, MathPow) \
7044  V(Math, max, MathMax) \
7045  V(Math, min, MathMin) \
7046  V(Math, imul, MathImul) \
7047  V(Math, clz32, MathClz32) \
7048  V(Math, fround, MathFround)
7049 
7050 enum BuiltinFunctionId {
7051  kArrayCode,
7052 #define DECLARE_FUNCTION_ID(ignored1, ignore2, name) \
7053  k##name,
7054  FUNCTIONS_WITH_ID_LIST(DECLARE_FUNCTION_ID)
7055 #undef DECLARE_FUNCTION_ID
7056  // Fake id for a special case of Math.pow. Note, it continues the
7057  // list of math functions.
7058  kMathPowHalf
7059 };

7490  class DeoptCountBits: public BitField<int, 0, 4> {};
7491  class OptReenableTriesBits: public BitField<int, 4, 18> {};
7492  class ICAgeBits: public BitField<int, 22, 8> {};
7493 
7494  class OptCountBits: public BitField<int, 0, 22> {};
7495  class DisabledOptimizationReasonBits: public BitField<int, 22, 8> {};
7496 
7497  private:
7498 #if V8_HOST_ARCH_32_BIT
7499  // On 32 bit platforms, compiler hints is a smi.
7500  static const int kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize = kSmiTagSize;
7501  static const int kCompilerHintsSize = kPointerSize;
7502 #else
7503  // On 64 bit platforms, compiler hints is not a smi, see comment above.
7504  static const int kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize = 0;
7505  static const int kCompilerHintsSize = kIntSize;
7506 #endif
7507 
7508  STATIC_ASSERT(SharedFunctionInfo::kCompilerHintsCount <=
7509  SharedFunctionInfo::kCompilerHintsSize * kBitsPerByte);
7510 
7511  public:
7512  // Constants for optimizing codegen for strict mode function and
7513  // native tests.
7514  // Allows to use byte-width instructions.
7515  static const int kStrictModeBitWithinByte =
7516  (kStrictModeFunction + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize) % kBitsPerByte;
7517 
7518  static const int kNativeBitWithinByte =
7519  (kNative + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize) % kBitsPerByte;
7520 
7521 #if defined(V8_TARGET_LITTLE_ENDIAN)
7522  static const int kStrictModeByteOffset = kCompilerHintsOffset +
7523  (kStrictModeFunction + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize) / kBitsPerByte;
7524  static const int kNativeByteOffset = kCompilerHintsOffset +
7525  (kNative + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize) / kBitsPerByte;
7526 #elif defined(V8_TARGET_BIG_ENDIAN)
7527  static const int kStrictModeByteOffset = kCompilerHintsOffset +
7528  (kCompilerHintsSize - 1) -
7529  ((kStrictModeFunction + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize) / kBitsPerByte);
7530  static const int kNativeByteOffset = kCompilerHintsOffset +
7531  (kCompilerHintsSize - 1) -
7532  ((kNative + kCompilerHintsSmiTagSize) / kBitsPerByte);
7533 #else
7534 #error Unknown byte ordering
7535 #endif
7536 
7537  private:
7538  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(SharedFunctionInfo);
7539 };

7703 
7704  // Inobject slack tracking is the way to reclaim unused inobject space.
7705  //
7706  // The instance size is initially determined by adding some slack to
7707  // expected_nof_properties (to allow for a few extra properties added
7708  // after the constructor). There is no guarantee that the extra space
7709  // will not be wasted.
7710  //
7711  // Here is the algorithm to reclaim the unused inobject space:
7712  // - Detect the first constructor call for this JSFunction.
7713  // When it happens enter the "in progress" state: initialize construction
7714  // counter in the initial_map and set the |done_inobject_slack_tracking|
7715  // flag.
7716  // - While the tracking is in progress create objects filled with
7717  // one_pointer_filler_map instead of undefined_value. This way they can be
7718  // resized quickly and safely.
7719  // - Once enough (kGenerousAllocationCount) objects have been created
7720  // compute the 'slack' (traverse the map transition tree starting from the
7721  // initial_map and find the lowest value of unused_property_fields).
7722  // - Traverse the transition tree again and decrease the instance size
7723  // of every map. Existing objects will resize automatically (they are
7724  // filled with one_pointer_filler_map). All further allocations will
7725  // use the adjusted instance size.
7726  // - SharedFunctionInfo's expected_nof_properties left unmodified since
7727  // allocations made using different closures could actually create different
7728  // kind of objects (see prototype inheritance pattern).
7729  //
7730  // Important: inobject slack tracking is not attempted during the snapshot
7731  // creation.
7732 
7733  static const int kGenerousAllocationCount = Map::ConstructionCount::kMax;
7734  static const int kFinishSlackTracking = 1;
7735  static const int kNoSlackTracking = 0;
7736 
7737  // True if the initial_map is set and the object constructions countdown
7738  // counter is not zero.
7739  inline bool IsInobjectSlackTrackingInProgress();
7740 
7741  // Starts the tracking.
7742  // Initializes object constructions countdown counter in the initial map.
7743  // IsInobjectSlackTrackingInProgress is normally true after this call,
7744  // except when tracking have not been started (e.g. the map has no unused
7745  // properties or the snapshot is being built).
7746  void StartInobjectSlackTracking();
7747 
7748  // Completes the tracking.
7749  // IsInobjectSlackTrackingInProgress is false after this call.
7750  void CompleteInobjectSlackTracking();
7751 
7752  // [literals_or_bindings]: Fixed array holding either
7753  // the materialized literals or the bindings of a bound function.
7754  //
7755  // If the function contains object, regexp or array literals, the
7756  // literals array prefix contains the object, regexp, and array
7757  // function to be used when creating these literals. This is
7758  // necessary so that we do not dynamically lookup the object, regexp
7759  // or array functions. Performing a dynamic lookup, we might end up
7760  // using the functions from a new context that we should not have
7761  // access to.
7762  //
7763  // On bound functions, the array is a (copy-on-write) fixed-array containing
7764  // the function that was bound, bound this-value and any bound
7765  // arguments. Bound functions never contain literals.
7766  DECL_ACCESSORS(literals_or_bindings, FixedArray)
7767 
7768  inline FixedArray* literals();
7769  inline void set_literals(FixedArray* literals);
7770 
7771  inline FixedArray* function_bindings();
7772  inline void set_function_bindings(FixedArray* bindings);
7773 
7774  // The initial map for an object created by this constructor.
7775  inline Map* initial_map();
7776  static void SetInitialMap(Handle<JSFunction> function, Handle<Map> map,

8165 
8166 // Regular expressions
8167 // The regular expression holds a single reference to a FixedArray in
8168 // the kDataOffset field.
8169 // The FixedArray contains the following data:
8170 // - tag : type of regexp implementation (not compiled yet, atom or irregexp)
8171 // - reference to the original source string
8172 // - reference to the original flag string
8173 // If it is an atom regexp
8174 // - a reference to a literal string to search for
8175 // If it is an irregexp regexp:
8176 // - a reference to code for ASCII inputs (bytecode or compiled), or a smi
8177 // used for tracking the last usage (used for code flushing).
8178 // - a reference to code for UC16 inputs (bytecode or compiled), or a smi
8179 // used for tracking the last usage (used for code flushing)..
8180 // - max number of registers used by irregexp implementations.
8181 // - number of capture registers (output values) of the regexp.
8182 class JSRegExp: public JSObject {
8183  public:
8184  // Meaning of Type:
8185  // NOT_COMPILED: Initial value. No data has been stored in the JSRegExp yet.
8186  // ATOM: A simple string to match against using an indexOf operation.
8187  // IRREGEXP: Compiled with Irregexp.
8188  // IRREGEXP_NATIVE: Compiled to native code with Irregexp.
8189  enum Type { NOT_COMPILED, ATOM, IRREGEXP };
8190  enum Flag { NONE = 0, GLOBAL = 1, IGNORE_CASE = 2, MULTILINE = 4 };
8191 
8192  class Flags {
8193  public:
8194  explicit Flags(uint32_t value) : value_(value) { }
8195  bool is_global() { return (value_ & GLOBAL) != 0; }
8196  bool is_ignore_case() { return (value_ & IGNORE_CASE) != 0; }
8197  bool is_multiline() { return (value_ & MULTILINE) != 0; }
8198  uint32_t value() { return value_; }
8199  private:
8200  uint32_t value_;
8201  };
8202 
8203  DECL_ACCESSORS(data, Object)
8204 
8205  inline Type TypeTag();
8206  inline int CaptureCount();
8207  inline Flags GetFlags();
8208  inline String* Pattern();
8209  inline Object* DataAt(int index);
8210  // Set implementation data after the object has been prepared.
8211  inline void SetDataAt(int index, Object* value);
8212 
8213  static int code_index(bool is_ascii) {
8214  if (is_ascii) {
8215  return kIrregexpASCIICodeIndex;
8216  } else {
8217  return kIrregexpUC16CodeIndex;
8218  }
8219  }
8220 
8221  static int saved_code_index(bool is_ascii) {
8222  if (is_ascii) {
8223  return kIrregexpASCIICodeSavedIndex;
8224  } else {
8225  return kIrregexpUC16CodeSavedIndex;
8226  }
8227  }
8228 
8229  DECLARE_CAST(JSRegExp)
8230 
8231  // Dispatched behavior.
8232  DECLARE_VERIFIER(JSRegExp)
8233 
8234  static const int kDataOffset = JSObject::kHeaderSize;
8235  static const int kSize = kDataOffset + kPointerSize;
8236 
8237  // Indices in the data array.
8238  static const int kTagIndex = 0;
8239  static const int kSourceIndex = kTagIndex + 1;
8240  static const int kFlagsIndex = kSourceIndex + 1;
8241  static const int kDataIndex = kFlagsIndex + 1;
8242  // The data fields are used in different ways depending on the
8243  // value of the tag.
8244  // Atom regexps (literal strings).
8245  static const int kAtomPatternIndex = kDataIndex;
8246 
8247  static const int kAtomDataSize = kAtomPatternIndex + 1;
8248 
8249  // Irregexp compiled code or bytecode for ASCII. If compilation
8250  // fails, this fields hold an exception object that should be
8251  // thrown if the regexp is used again.
8252  static const int kIrregexpASCIICodeIndex = kDataIndex;
8253  // Irregexp compiled code or bytecode for UC16. If compilation
8254  // fails, this fields hold an exception object that should be
8255  // thrown if the regexp is used again.
8256  static const int kIrregexpUC16CodeIndex = kDataIndex + 1;
8257 
8258  // Saved instance of Irregexp compiled code or bytecode for ASCII that
8259  // is a potential candidate for flushing.
8260  static const int kIrregexpASCIICodeSavedIndex = kDataIndex + 2;
8261  // Saved instance of Irregexp compiled code or bytecode for UC16 that is
8262  // a potential candidate for flushing.
8263  static const int kIrregexpUC16CodeSavedIndex = kDataIndex + 3;
8264 
8265  // Maximal number of registers used by either ASCII or UC16.
8266  // Only used to check that there is enough stack space
8267  static const int kIrregexpMaxRegisterCountIndex = kDataIndex + 4;
8268  // Number of captures in the compiled regexp.
8269  static const int kIrregexpCaptureCountIndex = kDataIndex + 5;
8270 
8271  static const int kIrregexpDataSize = kIrregexpCaptureCountIndex + 1;
8272 
8273  // Offsets directly into the data fixed array.
8274  static const int kDataTagOffset =
8275  FixedArray::kHeaderSize + kTagIndex * kPointerSize;
8276  static const int kDataAsciiCodeOffset =
8277  FixedArray::kHeaderSize + kIrregexpASCIICodeIndex * kPointerSize;
8278  static const int kDataUC16CodeOffset =
8279  FixedArray::kHeaderSize + kIrregexpUC16CodeIndex * kPointerSize;
8280  static const int kIrregexpCaptureCountOffset =
8281  FixedArray::kHeaderSize + kIrregexpCaptureCountIndex * kPointerSize;
8282 
8283  // In-object fields.
8284  static const int kSourceFieldIndex = 0;
8285  static const int kGlobalFieldIndex = 1;
8286  static const int kIgnoreCaseFieldIndex = 2;
8287  static const int kMultilineFieldIndex = 3;
8288  static const int kLastIndexFieldIndex = 4;
8289  static const int kInObjectFieldCount = 5;
8290 
8291  // The uninitialized value for a regexp code object.
8292  static const int kUninitializedValue = -1;
8293 
8294  // The compilation error value for the regexp code object. The real error
8295  // object is in the saved code field.
8296  static const int kCompilationErrorValue = -2;
8297 
8298  // When we store the sweep generation at which we moved the code from the
8299  // code index to the saved code index we mask it of to be in the [0:255]
8300  // range.
8301  static const int kCodeAgeMask = 0xff;
8302 };

8662  // The pretenuring decision is made during gc, and the zombie state allows
8663  // us to recognize when an allocation site is just being kept alive because
8664  // a later traversal of new space may discover AllocationMementos that point
8665  // to this AllocationSite.
8666  bool IsZombie() {

8820 class StringHasher {
8821  public:
8822  explicit inline StringHasher(int length, uint32_t seed);
8823 
8824  template <typename schar>
8825  static inline uint32_t HashSequentialString(const schar* chars,
8826  int length,
8827  uint32_t seed);
8828 
8829  // Reads all the data, even for long strings and computes the utf16 length.
8830  static uint32_t ComputeUtf8Hash(Vector<const char> chars,
8831  uint32_t seed,
8832  int* utf16_length_out);
8833 
8834  // Calculated hash value for a string consisting of 1 to
8835  // String::kMaxArrayIndexSize digits with no leading zeros (except "0").
8836  // value is represented decimal value.
8837  static uint32_t MakeArrayIndexHash(uint32_t value, int length);
8838 
8839  // No string is allowed to have a hash of zero. That value is reserved
8840  // for internal properties. If the hash calculation yields zero then we
8841  // use 27 instead.
8842  static const int kZeroHash = 27;
8843 
8844  // Reusable parts of the hashing algorithm.
8845  INLINE(static uint32_t AddCharacterCore(uint32_t running_hash, uint16_t c));
8846  INLINE(static uint32_t GetHashCore(uint32_t running_hash));
8847 
8848  protected:
8849  // Returns the value to store in the hash field of a string with
8850  // the given length and contents.
8851  uint32_t GetHashField();
8852  // Returns true if the hash of this string can be computed without
8853  // looking at the contents.
8854  inline bool has_trivial_hash();
8855  // Adds a block of characters to the hash.
8856  template<typename Char>
8857  inline void AddCharacters(const Char* chars, int len);
8858 
8859  private:
8860  // Add a character to the hash.
8861  inline void AddCharacter(uint16_t c);
8862  // Update index. Returns true if string is still an index.
8863  inline bool UpdateIndex(uint16_t c);
8864 
8865  int length_;
8866  uint32_t raw_running_hash_;
8867  uint32_t array_index_;
8868  bool is_array_index_;
8869  bool is_first_char_;
8870  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(StringHasher);
8871 };

8886 
8887 // The characteristics of a string are stored in its map. Retrieving these
8888 // few bits of information is moderately expensive, involving two memory
8889 // loads where the second is dependent on the first. To improve efficiency
8890 // the shape of the string is given its own class so that it can be retrieved
8891 // once and used for several string operations. A StringShape is small enough
8892 // to be passed by value and is immutable, but be aware that flattening a
8893 // string can potentially alter its shape. Also be aware that a GC caused by
8894 // something else can alter the shape of a string due to ConsString
8895 // shortcutting. Keeping these restrictions in mind has proven to be error-
8896 // prone and so we no longer put StringShapes in variables unless there is a
8897 // concrete performance benefit at that particular point in the code.
8898 class StringShape BASE_EMBEDDED {
8899  public:
8900  inline explicit StringShape(const String* s);
8901  inline explicit StringShape(Map* s);
8902  inline explicit StringShape(InstanceType t);
8903  inline bool IsSequential();
8904  inline bool IsExternal();
8905  inline bool IsCons();
8906  inline bool IsSliced();
8907  inline bool IsIndirect();
8908  inline bool IsExternalAscii();
8909  inline bool IsExternalTwoByte();
8910  inline bool IsSequentialAscii();
8911  inline bool IsSequentialTwoByte();
8912  inline bool IsInternalized();
8913  inline StringRepresentationTag representation_tag();
8914  inline uint32_t encoding_tag();
8915  inline uint32_t full_representation_tag();
8916  inline uint32_t size_tag();
8917 #ifdef DEBUG
8918  inline uint32_t type() { return type_; }
8919  inline void invalidate() { valid_ = false; }
8920  inline bool valid() { return valid_; }
8921 #else
8922  inline void invalidate() { }
8923 #endif
8924 
8925  private:
8926  uint32_t type_;
8927 #ifdef DEBUG
8928  inline void set_valid() { valid_ = true; }
8929  bool valid_;
8930 #else
8931  inline void set_valid() { }
8932 #endif
8933 };

8935 
8936 // The Name abstract class captures anything that can be used as a property
8937 // name, i.e., strings and symbols. All names store a hash value.
8938 class Name: public HeapObject {
8939  public:
8940  // Get and set the hash field of the name.
8941  inline uint32_t hash_field();
8942  inline void set_hash_field(uint32_t value);
8943 
8944  // Tells whether the hash code has been computed.
8945  inline bool HasHashCode();
8946 
8947  // Returns a hash value used for the property table
8948  inline uint32_t Hash();
8949 
8950  // Equality operations.
8951  inline bool Equals(Name* other);
8952  inline static bool Equals(Handle<Name> one, Handle<Name> two);
8953 
8954  // Conversion.
8955  inline bool AsArrayIndex(uint32_t* index);
8956 
8957  // Whether name can only name own properties.
8958  inline bool IsOwn();
8959 
8960  DECLARE_CAST(Name)
8961 
8962  DECLARE_PRINTER(Name)
8963 
8964  // Layout description.
8965  static const int kHashFieldOffset = HeapObject::kHeaderSize;
8966  static const int kSize = kHashFieldOffset + kPointerSize;
8967 
8968  // Mask constant for checking if a name has a computed hash code
8969  // and if it is a string that is an array index. The least significant bit
8970  // indicates whether a hash code has been computed. If the hash code has
8971  // been computed the 2nd bit tells whether the string can be used as an
8972  // array index.
8973  static const int kHashNotComputedMask = 1;
8974  static const int kIsNotArrayIndexMask = 1 << 1;
8975  static const int kNofHashBitFields = 2;
8976 
8977  // Shift constant retrieving hash code from hash field.
8978  static const int kHashShift = kNofHashBitFields;
8979 
8980  // Only these bits are relevant in the hash, since the top two are shifted
8981  // out.
8982  static const uint32_t kHashBitMask = 0xffffffffu >> kHashShift;
8983 
8984  // Array index strings this short can keep their index in the hash field.
8985  static const int kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength = 7;
8986 
8987  // For strings which are array indexes the hash value has the string length
8988  // mixed into the hash, mainly to avoid a hash value of zero which would be
8989  // the case for the string '0'. 24 bits are used for the array index value.
8990  static const int kArrayIndexValueBits = 24;
8991  static const int kArrayIndexLengthBits =
8992  kBitsPerInt - kArrayIndexValueBits - kNofHashBitFields;
8993 
8994  STATIC_ASSERT((kArrayIndexLengthBits > 0));
8995 
8996  class ArrayIndexValueBits : public BitField<unsigned int, kNofHashBitFields,
8997  kArrayIndexValueBits> {}; // NOLINT
8998  class ArrayIndexLengthBits : public BitField<unsigned int,
8999  kNofHashBitFields + kArrayIndexValueBits,
9000  kArrayIndexLengthBits> {}; // NOLINT
9001 
9002  // Check that kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength + 1 is a power of two so we
9003  // could use a mask to test if the length of string is less than or equal to
9004  // kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength.
9005  STATIC_ASSERT(IS_POWER_OF_TWO(kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength + 1));
9006 
9007  static const unsigned int kContainsCachedArrayIndexMask =
9008  (~static_cast<unsigned>(kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength)
9009  << ArrayIndexLengthBits::kShift) |
9010  kIsNotArrayIndexMask;
9011 
9012  // Value of empty hash field indicating that the hash is not computed.
9013  static const int kEmptyHashField =
9014  kIsNotArrayIndexMask | kHashNotComputedMask;
9015 
9016  protected:
9017  static inline bool IsHashFieldComputed(uint32_t field);
9018 
9019  private:
9020  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(Name);
9021 };

9060 class ConsString;
9061 
9062 // The String abstract class captures JavaScript string values:
9063 //
9064 // Ecma-262:
9065 // 4.3.16 String Value
9066 // A string value is a member of the type String and is a finite
9067 // ordered sequence of zero or more 16-bit unsigned integer values.
9068 //
9069 // All string values have a length field.
9070 class String: public Name {
9071  public:
9072  enum Encoding { ONE_BYTE_ENCODING, TWO_BYTE_ENCODING };
9073 
9074  // Array index strings this short can keep their index in the hash field.
9075  static const int kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength = 7;
9076 
9077  // For strings which are array indexes the hash value has the string length
9078  // mixed into the hash, mainly to avoid a hash value of zero which would be
9079  // the case for the string '0'. 24 bits are used for the array index value.
9080  static const int kArrayIndexValueBits = 24;
9081  static const int kArrayIndexLengthBits =
9082  kBitsPerInt - kArrayIndexValueBits - kNofHashBitFields;
9083 
9084  STATIC_ASSERT((kArrayIndexLengthBits > 0));
9085 
9086  class ArrayIndexValueBits : public BitField<unsigned int, kNofHashBitFields,
9087  kArrayIndexValueBits> {}; // NOLINT
9088  class ArrayIndexLengthBits : public BitField<unsigned int,
9089  kNofHashBitFields + kArrayIndexValueBits,
9090  kArrayIndexLengthBits> {}; // NOLINT
9091 
9092  // Check that kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength + 1 is a power of two so we
9093  // could use a mask to test if the length of string is less than or equal to
9094  // kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength.
9095  STATIC_ASSERT(IS_POWER_OF_TWO(kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength + 1));
9096 
9097  static const unsigned int kContainsCachedArrayIndexMask =
9098  (~static_cast<unsigned>(kMaxCachedArrayIndexLength)
9099  << ArrayIndexLengthBits::kShift) |
9100  kIsNotArrayIndexMask;
9101 
9102  // Representation of the flat content of a String.
9103  // A non-flat string doesn't have flat content.
9104  // A flat string has content that's encoded as a sequence of either
9105  // ASCII chars or two-byte UC16.
9106  // Returned by String::GetFlatContent().
9107  class FlatContent {
9108  public:
9109  // Returns true if the string is flat and this structure contains content.
9110  bool IsFlat() { return state_ != NON_FLAT; }
9111  // Returns true if the structure contains ASCII content.
9112  bool IsAscii() { return state_ == ASCII; }
9113  // Returns true if the structure contains two-byte content.
9114  bool IsTwoByte() { return state_ == TWO_BYTE; }
9115 
9116  // Return the one byte content of the string. Only use if IsAscii() returns
9117  // true.
9118  Vector<const uint8_t> ToOneByteVector() {
9119  DCHECK_EQ(ASCII, state_);
9120  return Vector<const uint8_t>(onebyte_start, length_);
9121  }
9122  // Return the two-byte content of the string. Only use if IsTwoByte()
9123  // returns true.
9124  Vector<const uc16> ToUC16Vector() {
9125  DCHECK_EQ(TWO_BYTE, state_);
9126  return Vector<const uc16>(twobyte_start, length_);
9127  }
9128 
9129  uc16 Get(int i) {
9130  DCHECK(i < length_);
9131  DCHECK(state_ != NON_FLAT);
9132  if (state_ == ASCII) return onebyte_start[i];
9133  return twobyte_start[i];
9134  }
9135 
9136  private:
9137  enum State { NON_FLAT, ASCII, TWO_BYTE };
9138 
9139  // Constructors only used by String::GetFlatContent().
9140  explicit FlatContent(const uint8_t* start, int length)
9141  : onebyte_start(start), length_(length), state_(ASCII) { }
9142  explicit FlatContent(const uc16* start, int length)
9143  : twobyte_start(start), length_(length), state_(TWO_BYTE) { }
9144  FlatContent() : onebyte_start(NULL), length_(0), state_(NON_FLAT) { }
9145 
9146  union {
9147  const uint8_t* onebyte_start;
9148  const uc16* twobyte_start;
9149  };
9150  int length_;
9151  State state_;
9152 
9153  friend class String;
9154  };
9155 
9156  // Get and set the length of the string.
9157  inline int length() const;
9158  inline void set_length(int value);
9159 
9160  // Get and set the length of the string using acquire loads and release
9161  // stores.
9162  inline int synchronized_length() const;
9163  inline void synchronized_set_length(int value);
9164 
9165  // Returns whether this string has only ASCII chars, i.e. all of them can
9166  // be ASCII encoded. This might be the case even if the string is
9167  // two-byte. Such strings may appear when the embedder prefers
9168  // two-byte external representations even for ASCII data.
9169  inline bool IsOneByteRepresentation() const;
9170  inline bool IsTwoByteRepresentation() const;
9171 
9172  // Cons and slices have an encoding flag that may not represent the actual
9173  // encoding of the underlying string. This is taken into account here.
9174  // Requires: this->IsFlat()
9175  inline bool IsOneByteRepresentationUnderneath();
9176  inline bool IsTwoByteRepresentationUnderneath();
9177 
9178  // NOTE: this should be considered only a hint. False negatives are
9179  // possible.
9180  inline bool HasOnlyOneByteChars();
9181 
9182  // Get and set individual two byte chars in the string.
9183  inline void Set(int index, uint16_t value);
9184  // Get individual two byte char in the string. Repeated calls
9185  // to this method are not efficient unless the string is flat.
9186  INLINE(uint16_t Get(int index));
9187 
9188  // Flattens the string. Checks first inline to see if it is
9189  // necessary. Does nothing if the string is not a cons string.
9190  // Flattening allocates a sequential string with the same data as
9191  // the given string and mutates the cons string to a degenerate
9192  // form, where the first component is the new sequential string and
9193  // the second component is the empty string. If allocation fails,
9194  // this function returns a failure. If flattening succeeds, this
9195  // function returns the sequential string that is now the first
9196  // component of the cons string.
9197  //
9198  // Degenerate cons strings are handled specially by the garbage
9199  // collector (see IsShortcutCandidate).
9200 
9201  static inline Handle<String> Flatten(Handle<String> string,
9202  PretenureFlag pretenure = NOT_TENURED);
9203 
9204  // Tries to return the content of a flat string as a structure holding either
9205  // a flat vector of char or of uc16.
9206  // If the string isn't flat, and therefore doesn't have flat content, the
9207  // returned structure will report so, and can't provide a vector of either
9208  // kind.
9209  FlatContent GetFlatContent();
9210 
9211  // Returns the parent of a sliced string or first part of a flat cons string.
9212  // Requires: StringShape(this).IsIndirect() && this->IsFlat()
9213  inline String* GetUnderlying();
9214

9216  // ASCII and two byte string types.
9217  bool MarkAsUndetectable();
9218

9220  inline bool Equals(String* other);
9221  inline static bool Equals(Handle<String> one, Handle<String> two);

9224  bool IsTwoByteEqualTo(Vector<const uc16> str);

9226  // Return a UTF8 representation of the string. The string is null
9227  // terminated but may optionally contain nulls. Length is returned
9228  // in length_output if length_output is not a null pointer The string
9229  // should be nearly flat, otherwise the performance of this method may
9230  // be very slow (quadratic in the length). Setting robustness_flag to
9231  // ROBUST_STRING_TRAVERSAL invokes behaviour that is robust This means it
9232  // handles unexpected data without causing assert failures and it does not

9285  // value into an array index.

9287  STATIC_ASSERT(kMaxArrayIndexSize < (1 << kArrayIndexLengthBits));

9290  static const int32_t kMaxOneByteCharCode = unibrow::Latin1::kMaxChar;
9291  static const uint32_t kMaxOneByteCharCodeU = unibrow::Latin1::kMaxChar;
9292  static const int kMaxUtf16CodeUnit = 0xffff;
9293  static const uint32_t kMaxUtf16CodeUnitU = kMaxUtf16CodeUnit;
9294 
9295  // Value of hash field containing computed hash equal to zero.
9296  static const int kEmptyStringHash = kIsNotArrayIndexMask;
9297 
9298  // Maximal string length.
9299  static const int kMaxLength = (1 << 28) - 16;
9300 
9301  // Max length for computing hash. For strings longer than this limit the
9302  // string length is used as the hash value.
9303  static const int kMaxHashCalcLength = 16383;

9306  static const int kMaxShortPrintLength = 1024;

9311  // Helper function for flattening strings.
9312  template <typename sinkchar>
9313  static void WriteToFlat(String* source,
9314  sinkchar* sink,
9315  int from,
9316  int to);
9317 
9318  // The return value may point to the first aligned word containing the
9319  // first non-ascii character, rather than directly to the non-ascii character.
9320  // If the return value is >= the passed length, the entire string was ASCII.
9321  static inline int NonAsciiStart(const char* chars, int length) {
9322  const char* start = chars;
9323  const char* limit = chars + length;
9324 #ifdef V8_HOST_CAN_READ_UNALIGNED
9325  DCHECK(unibrow::Utf8::kMaxOneByteChar == 0x7F);
9326  const uintptr_t non_ascii_mask = kUintptrAllBitsSet / 0xFF * 0x80;
9327  while (chars + sizeof(uintptr_t) <= limit) {
9328  if (*reinterpret_cast<const uintptr_t*>(chars) & non_ascii_mask) {
9329  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9330  }
9331  chars += sizeof(uintptr_t);
9332  }
9333 #endif
9334  while (chars < limit) {
9335  if (static_cast<uint8_t>(*chars) > unibrow::Utf8::kMaxOneByteChar) {
9336  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9337  }
9338  ++chars;
9339  }
9340  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9341  }
9342 
9343  static inline bool IsAscii(const char* chars, int length) {
9344  return NonAsciiStart(chars, length) >= length;
9345  }
9346 
9347  static inline bool IsAscii(const uint8_t* chars, int length) {
9348  return
9349  NonAsciiStart(reinterpret_cast<const char*>(chars), length) >= length;
9350  }
9351 
9352  static inline int NonOneByteStart(const uc16* chars, int length) {
9353  const uc16* limit = chars + length;
9354  const uc16* start = chars;
9355  while (chars < limit) {
9356  if (*chars > kMaxOneByteCharCodeU) return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9357  ++chars;
9358  }
9359  return static_cast<int>(chars - start);
9360  }
9361 
9362  static inline bool IsOneByte(const uc16* chars, int length) {
9363  return NonOneByteStart(chars, length) >= length;
9364  }
9365 
9366  template<class Visitor>
9367  static inline ConsString* VisitFlat(Visitor* visitor,
9368  String* string,
9369  int offset = 0);
9370 
9371  static Handle<FixedArray> CalculateLineEnds(Handle<String> string,
9372  bool include_ending_line);
9373 
9374  // Use the hash field to forward to the canonical internalized string
9375  // when deserializing an internalized string.
9376  inline void SetForwardedInternalizedString(String* string);
9377  inline String* GetForwardedInternalizedString();
9378 
9379  private:
9380  friend class Name;
9381  friend class StringTableInsertionKey;
9382 
9383  static Handle<String> SlowFlatten(Handle<ConsString> cons,
9384  PretenureFlag tenure);
9385

9387  // but it is most efficient on strings that are almost flat.
9388  bool SlowEquals(String* other);
9389 
9390  static bool SlowEquals(Handle<String> one, Handle<String> two);

9394

9496 // The ConsString class describes string values built by using the
9497 // addition operator on strings. A ConsString is a pair where the
9498 // first and second components are pointers to other string values.
9499 // One or both components of a ConsString can be pointers to other
9500 // ConsStrings, creating a binary tree of ConsStrings where the leaves
9501 // are non-ConsString string values. The string value represented by
9502 // a ConsString can be obtained by concatenating the leaf string
9503 // values in a left-to-right depth-first traversal of the tree.
9504 class ConsString: public String {
9505  public:
9506  // First string of the cons cell.
9507  inline String* first();
9508  // Doesn't check that the result is a string, even in debug mode. This is
9509  // useful during GC where the mark bits confuse the checks.
9510  inline Object* unchecked_first();
9511  inline void set_first(String* first,
9512  WriteBarrierMode mode = UPDATE_WRITE_BARRIER);
9513 
9514  // Second string of the cons cell.
9515  inline String* second();
9516  // Doesn't check that the result is a string, even in debug mode. This is
9517  // useful during GC where the mark bits confuse the checks.
9518  inline Object* unchecked_second();
9519  inline void set_second(String* second,
9520  WriteBarrierMode mode = UPDATE_WRITE_BARRIER);
9521 
9522  // Dispatched behavior.
9523  uint16_t ConsStringGet(int index);
9524 
9525  DECLARE_CAST(ConsString)
9526 
9527  // Layout description.
9528  static const int kFirstOffset = POINTER_SIZE_ALIGN(String::kSize);
9529  static const int kSecondOffset = kFirstOffset + kPointerSize;
9530  static const int kSize = kSecondOffset + kPointerSize;
9531 
9532  // Minimum length for a cons string.
9533  static const int kMinLength = 13;
9534 
9535  typedef FixedBodyDescriptor<kFirstOffset, kSecondOffset + kPointerSize, kSize>
9536  BodyDescriptor;
9537 
9538  DECLARE_VERIFIER(ConsString)
9539 
9540  private:
9541  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(ConsString);
9542 };

9545 // The Sliced String class describes strings that are substrings of another
9546 // sequential string. The motivation is to save time and memory when creating
9547 // a substring. A Sliced String is described as a pointer to the parent,
9548 // the offset from the start of the parent string and the length. Using
9549 // a Sliced String therefore requires unpacking of the parent string and
9550 // adding the offset to the start address. A substring of a Sliced String
9551 // are not nested since the double indirection is simplified when creating
9552 // such a substring.
9553 // Currently missing features are:
9554 // - handling externalized parent strings
9555 // - external strings as parent
9556 // - truncating sliced string to enable otherwise unneeded parent to be GC'ed.
9557 class SlicedString: public String {
9558  public:
9559  inline String* parent();
9560  inline void set_parent(String* parent,
9561  WriteBarrierMode mode = UPDATE_WRITE_BARRIER);
9562  inline int offset() const;
9563  inline void set_offset(int offset);
9564 
9565  // Dispatched behavior.
9566  uint16_t SlicedStringGet(int index);
9567 
9568  DECLARE_CAST(SlicedString)
9569 
9570  // Layout description.
9571  static const int kParentOffset = POINTER_SIZE_ALIGN(String::kSize);
9572  static const int kOffsetOffset = kParentOffset + kPointerSize;
9573  static const int kSize = kOffsetOffset + kPointerSize;
9574 
9575  // Minimum length for a sliced string.
9576  static const int kMinLength = 13;
9577 
9578  typedef FixedBodyDescriptor<kParentOffset,
9579  kOffsetOffset + kPointerSize, kSize>
9580  BodyDescriptor;
9581 
9582  DECLARE_VERIFIER(SlicedString)
9583 
9584  private:
9585  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(SlicedString);
9586 };

9589 // The ExternalString class describes string values that are backed by
9590 // a string resource that lies outside the V8 heap. ExternalStrings
9591 // consist of the length field common to all strings, a pointer to the
9592 // external resource. It is important to ensure (externally) that the
9593 // resource is not deallocated while the ExternalString is live in the
9594 // V8 heap.
9595 //
9596 // The API expects that all ExternalStrings are created through the
9597 // API. Therefore, ExternalStrings should not be used internally.
9598 class ExternalString: public String {
9599  public:
9600  DECLARE_CAST(ExternalString)
9601 
9602  // Layout description.
9603  static const int kResourceOffset = POINTER_SIZE_ALIGN(String::kSize);
9604  static const int kShortSize = kResourceOffset + kPointerSize;
9605  static const int kResourceDataOffset = kResourceOffset + kPointerSize;
9606  static const int kSize = kResourceDataOffset + kPointerSize;
9607 
9608  static const int kMaxShortLength =
9609  (kShortSize - SeqString::kHeaderSize) / kCharSize;

9611  // Return whether external string is short (data pointer is not cached).
9612  inline bool is_short();

9750 // This maintains an off-stack representation of the stack frames required
9751 // to traverse a ConsString, allowing an entirely iterative and restartable
9752 // traversal of the entire string
9753 class ConsStringIteratorOp {
9754  public:
9755  inline ConsStringIteratorOp() {}
9756  inline explicit ConsStringIteratorOp(ConsString* cons_string,
9757  int offset = 0) {
9758  Reset(cons_string, offset);
9759  }
9760  inline void Reset(ConsString* cons_string, int offset = 0) {
9761  depth_ = 0;
9762  // Next will always return NULL.
9763  if (cons_string == NULL) return;
9764  Initialize(cons_string, offset);
9765  }
9766  // Returns NULL when complete.
9767  inline String* Next(int* offset_out) {
9768  *offset_out = 0;
9769  if (depth_ == 0) return NULL;
9770  return Continue(offset_out);
9771  }
9772 
9773  private:
9774  static const int kStackSize = 32;
9775  // Use a mask instead of doing modulo operations for stack wrapping.
9776  static const int kDepthMask = kStackSize-1;
9777  STATIC_ASSERT(IS_POWER_OF_TWO(kStackSize));
9778  static inline int OffsetForDepth(int depth);
9779 
9780  inline void PushLeft(ConsString* string);
9781  inline void PushRight(ConsString* string);
9782  inline void AdjustMaximumDepth();
9783  inline void Pop();
9784  inline bool StackBlown() { return maximum_depth_ - depth_ == kStackSize; }
9785  void Initialize(ConsString* cons_string, int offset);
9786  String* Continue(int* offset_out);
9787  String* NextLeaf(bool* blew_stack);
9788  String* Search(int* offset_out);
9789 
9790  // Stack must always contain only frames for which right traversal
9791  // has not yet been performed.
9792  ConsString* frames_[kStackSize];
9793  ConsString* root_;
9794  int depth_;
9795  int maximum_depth_;
9796  int consumed_;
9797  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(ConsStringIteratorOp);
9798 };

9978 // The JSProxy describes EcmaScript Harmony proxies
9979 class JSProxy: public JSReceiver {
9980  public:
9981  // [handler]: The handler property.
9982  DECL_ACCESSORS(handler, Object)
9983 
9984  // [hash]: The hash code property (undefined if not initialized yet).
9985  DECL_ACCESSORS(hash, Object)
9986 
9987  DECLARE_CAST(JSProxy)
9988 
9989  MUST_USE_RESULT static MaybeHandle<Object> GetPropertyWithHandler(
9990  Handle<JSProxy> proxy,
9991  Handle<Object> receiver,
9992  Handle<Name> name);
9993  MUST_USE_RESULT static inline MaybeHandle<Object> GetElementWithHandler(
9994  Handle<JSProxy> proxy,
9995  Handle<Object> receiver,
9996  uint32_t index);
9997 
9998  // If the handler defines an accessor property with a setter, invoke it.
9999  // If it defines an accessor property without a setter, or a data property
10000  // that is read-only, throw. In all these cases set '*done' to true,
10001  // otherwise set it to false.
10002  MUST_USE_RESULT
10003  static MaybeHandle<Object> SetPropertyViaPrototypesWithHandler(
10004  Handle<JSProxy> proxy, Handle<Object> receiver, Handle<Name> name,
10005  Handle<Object> value, StrictMode strict_mode, bool* done);
10006 
10007  MUST_USE_RESULT static Maybe<PropertyAttributes>
10008  GetPropertyAttributesWithHandler(Handle<JSProxy> proxy,
10009  Handle<Object> receiver,
10010  Handle<Name> name);
10011  MUST_USE_RESULT static Maybe<PropertyAttributes>
10012  GetElementAttributeWithHandler(Handle<JSProxy> proxy,
10013  Handle<JSReceiver> receiver,
10014  uint32_t index);
10015  MUST_USE_RESULT static MaybeHandle<Object> SetPropertyWithHandler(
10016  Handle<JSProxy> proxy, Handle<Object> receiver, Handle<Name> name,
10017  Handle<Object> value, StrictMode strict_mode);
10018 
10019  // Turn the proxy into an (empty) JSObject.
10020  static void Fix(Handle<JSProxy> proxy);
10021 
10022  // Initializes the body after the handler slot.
10023  inline void InitializeBody(int object_size, Object* value);
10024 
10025  // Invoke a trap by name. If the trap does not exist on this's handler,
10026  // but derived_trap is non-NULL, invoke that instead. May cause GC.
10027  MUST_USE_RESULT static MaybeHandle<Object> CallTrap(
10028  Handle<JSProxy> proxy,
10029  const char* name,
10030  Handle<Object> derived_trap,
10031  int argc,
10032  Handle<Object> args[]);
10033 
10034  // Dispatched behavior.
10035  DECLARE_PRINTER(JSProxy)
10036  DECLARE_VERIFIER(JSProxy)
10037 
10038  // Layout description. We add padding so that a proxy has the same
10039  // size as a virgin JSObject. This is essential for becoming a JSObject
10040  // upon freeze.
10041  static const int kHandlerOffset = HeapObject::kHeaderSize;
10042  static const int kHashOffset = kHandlerOffset + kPointerSize;
10043  static const int kPaddingOffset = kHashOffset + kPointerSize;
10044  static const int kSize = JSObject::kHeaderSize;
10045  static const int kHeaderSize = kPaddingOffset;
10046  static const int kPaddingSize = kSize - kPaddingOffset;
10047 
10048  STATIC_ASSERT(kPaddingSize >= 0);
10049 
10050  typedef FixedBodyDescriptor<kHandlerOffset,
10051  kPaddingOffset,
10052  kSize> BodyDescriptor;
10053 
10054  private:
10055  friend class JSReceiver;
10056 
10057  MUST_USE_RESULT static inline MaybeHandle<Object> SetElementWithHandler(
10058  Handle<JSProxy> proxy,
10059  Handle<JSReceiver> receiver,
10060  uint32_t index,
10061  Handle<Object> value,
10062  StrictMode strict_mode);
10063 
10064  MUST_USE_RESULT static Maybe<bool> HasPropertyWithHandler(
10065  Handle<JSProxy> proxy, Handle<Name> name);
10066  MUST_USE_RESULT static inline Maybe<bool> HasElementWithHandler(
10067  Handle<JSProxy> proxy, uint32_t index);
10068 
10069  MUST_USE_RESULT static MaybeHandle<Object> DeletePropertyWithHandler(
10070  Handle<JSProxy> proxy,
10071  Handle<Name> name,
10072  DeleteMode mode);
10073  MUST_USE_RESULT static MaybeHandle<Object> DeleteElementWithHandler(
10074  Handle<JSProxy> proxy,
10075  uint32_t index,
10076  DeleteMode mode);
10077 
10078  MUST_USE_RESULT Object* GetIdentityHash();
10079 
10080  static Handle<Smi> GetOrCreateIdentityHash(Handle<JSProxy> proxy);
10081 
10082  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(JSProxy);
10083 };

10158 
10159 // OrderedHashTableIterator is an iterator that iterates over the keys and
10160 // values of an OrderedHashTable.
10161 //
10162 // The iterator has a reference to the underlying OrderedHashTable data,
10163 // [table], as well as the current [index] the iterator is at.
10164 //
10165 // When the OrderedHashTable is rehashed it adds a reference from the old table
10166 // to the new table as well as storing enough data about the changes so that the
10167 // iterator [index] can be adjusted accordingly.
10168 //
10169 // When the [Next] result from the iterator is requested, the iterator checks if
10170 // there is a newer table that it needs to transition to.
10171 template<class Derived, class TableType>
10172 class OrderedHashTableIterator: public JSObject {
10173  public:
10174  // [table]: the backing hash table mapping keys to values.
10175  DECL_ACCESSORS(table, Object)
10176 
10177  // [index]: The index into the data table.
10178  DECL_ACCESSORS(index, Smi)
10179 
10180  // [kind]: The kind of iteration this is. One of the [Kind] enum values.
10181  DECL_ACCESSORS(kind, Smi)
10182 
10183 #ifdef OBJECT_PRINT
10184  void OrderedHashTableIteratorPrint(OStream& os); // NOLINT
10185 #endif
10186 
10187  static const int kTableOffset = JSObject::kHeaderSize;
10188  static const int kIndexOffset = kTableOffset + kPointerSize;
10189  static const int kKindOffset = kIndexOffset + kPointerSize;
10190  static const int kSize = kKindOffset + kPointerSize;
10191 
10192  enum Kind {
10193  kKindKeys = 1,
10194  kKindValues = 2,
10195  kKindEntries = 3
10196  };
10197 
10198  // Whether the iterator has more elements. This needs to be called before
10199  // calling |CurrentKey| and/or |CurrentValue|.
10200  bool HasMore();
10201 
10202  // Move the index forward one.
10203  void MoveNext() {
10204  set_index(Smi::FromInt(Smi::cast(index())->value() + 1));
10205  }
10206 
10207  // Populates the array with the next key and value and then moves the iterator
10208  // forward.
10209  // This returns the |kind| or 0 if the iterator is already at the end.
10210  Smi* Next(JSArray* value_array);
10211 
10212  // Returns the current key of the iterator. This should only be called when
10213  // |HasMore| returns true.
10214  inline Object* CurrentKey();
10215 
10216  private:
10217  // Transitions the iterator to the non obsolete backing store. This is a NOP
10218  // if the [table] is not obsolete.
10219  void Transition();
10220 
10221  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(OrderedHashTableIterator);
10222 };
10223 
10224 
10225 class JSSetIterator: public OrderedHashTableIterator<JSSetIterator,
10226  OrderedHashSet> {
10227  public:
10228  // Dispatched behavior.
10229  DECLARE_PRINTER(JSSetIterator)
10230  DECLARE_VERIFIER(JSSetIterator)

10481 // The JSArray describes JavaScript Arrays
10482 // Such an array can be in one of two modes:
10483 // - fast, backing storage is a FixedArray and length <= elements.length();
10484 // Please note: push and pop can be used to grow and shrink the array.
10485 // - slow, backing storage is a HashTable with numbers as keys.
10486 class JSArray: public JSObject {
10487  public:
10488  // [length]: The length property.
10489  DECL_ACCESSORS(length, Object)
10490 
10491  // Overload the length setter to skip write barrier when the length
10492  // is set to a smi. This matches the set function on FixedArray.
10493  inline void set_length(Smi* length);
10494 
10495  static void JSArrayUpdateLengthFromIndex(Handle<JSArray> array,
10496  uint32_t index,
10497  Handle<Object> value);
10498 
10499  static bool IsReadOnlyLengthDescriptor(Handle<Map> jsarray_map);
10500  static bool WouldChangeReadOnlyLength(Handle<JSArray> array, uint32_t index);
10501  static MaybeHandle<Object> ReadOnlyLengthError(Handle<JSArray> array);
10502 
10503  // Initialize the array with the given capacity. The function may
10504  // fail due to out-of-memory situations, but only if the requested
10505  // capacity is non-zero.
10506  static void Initialize(Handle<JSArray> array, int capacity, int length = 0);
10507 
10508  // Initializes the array to a certain length.
10509  inline bool AllowsSetElementsLength();
10510  // Can cause GC.
10511  MUST_USE_RESULT static MaybeHandle<Object> SetElementsLength(
10512  Handle<JSArray> array,
10513  Handle<Object> length);
10514 
10515  // Set the content of the array to the content of storage.
10516  static inline void SetContent(Handle<JSArray> array,
10517  Handle<FixedArrayBase> storage);
10518 
10519  DECLARE_CAST(JSArray)
10520 
10521  // Ensures that the fixed array backing the JSArray has at
10522  // least the stated size.
10523  static inline void EnsureSize(Handle<JSArray> array,
10524  int minimum_size_of_backing_fixed_array);
10525 
10526  // Expand the fixed array backing of a fast-case JSArray to at least
10527  // the requested size.
10528  static void Expand(Handle<JSArray> array,
10529  int minimum_size_of_backing_fixed_array);
10530 
10531  // Dispatched behavior.
10532  DECLARE_PRINTER(JSArray)
10533  DECLARE_VERIFIER(JSArray)
10534 
10535  // Number of element slots to pre-allocate for an empty array.
10536  static const int kPreallocatedArrayElements = 4;
10537 
10538  // Layout description.
10539  static const int kLengthOffset = JSObject::kHeaderSize;
10540  static const int kSize = kLengthOffset + kPointerSize;
10541 
10542  private:
10543  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(JSArray);
10544 };

10729 
10730 // An accessor must have a getter, but can have no setter.
10731 //
10732 // When setting a property, V8 searches accessors in prototypes.
10733 // If an accessor was found and it does not have a setter,
10734 // the request is ignored.
10735 //
10736 // If the accessor in the prototype has the READ_ONLY property attribute, then
10737 // a new value is added to the derived object when the property is set.
10738 // This shadows the accessor in the prototype.
10739 class ExecutableAccessorInfo: public AccessorInfo {
10740  public:
10741  DECL_ACCESSORS(getter, Object)
10742  DECL_ACCESSORS(setter, Object)
10743  DECL_ACCESSORS(data, Object)
10744 
10745  DECLARE_CAST(ExecutableAccessorInfo)
10746 
10747  // Dispatched behavior.
10748  DECLARE_PRINTER(ExecutableAccessorInfo)
10749  DECLARE_VERIFIER(ExecutableAccessorInfo)
10750 
10751  static const int kGetterOffset = AccessorInfo::kSize;
10752  static const int kSetterOffset = kGetterOffset + kPointerSize;
10753  static const int kDataOffset = kSetterOffset + kPointerSize;
10754  static const int kSize = kDataOffset + kPointerSize;
10755 
10756  inline void clear_setter();
10757 
10758  private:
10759  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(ExecutableAccessorInfo);
10760 };
10761 
10762 
10763 // Support for JavaScript accessors: A pair of a getter and a setter. Each
10764 // accessor can either be
10765 // * a pointer to a JavaScript function or proxy: a real accessor
10766 // * undefined: considered an accessor by the spec, too, strangely enough
10767 // * the hole: an accessor which has not been set
10768 // * a pointer to a map: a transition used to ensure map sharing
10769 class AccessorPair: public Struct {
10770  public:
10771  DECL_ACCESSORS(getter, Object)
10772  DECL_ACCESSORS(setter, Object)
10773 
10774  DECLARE_CAST(AccessorPair)
10775 
10776  static Handle<AccessorPair> Copy(Handle<AccessorPair> pair);
10777 
10778  Object* get(AccessorComponent component) {
10779  return component == ACCESSOR_GETTER ? getter() : setter();
10780  }
10781 
10782  void set(AccessorComponent component, Object* value) {
10783  if (component == ACCESSOR_GETTER) {
10784  set_getter(value);
10785  } else {
10786  set_setter(value);
10787  }
10788  }
10789 
10790  // Note: Returns undefined instead in case of a hole.
10791  Object* GetComponent(AccessorComponent component);
10792 
10793  // Set both components, skipping arguments which are a JavaScript null.
10794  void SetComponents(Object* getter, Object* setter) {
10795  if (!getter->IsNull()) set_getter(getter);
10796  if (!setter->IsNull()) set_setter(setter);
10797  }
10798 
10799  bool ContainsAccessor() {
10800  return IsJSAccessor(getter()) || IsJSAccessor(setter());
10801  }
10802 
10803  // Dispatched behavior.
10804  DECLARE_PRINTER(AccessorPair)
10805  DECLARE_VERIFIER(AccessorPair)
10806 
10807  static const int kGetterOffset = HeapObject::kHeaderSize;
10808  static const int kSetterOffset = kGetterOffset + kPointerSize;
10809  static const int kSize = kSetterOffset + kPointerSize;
10810 
10811  private:
10812  // Strangely enough, in addition to functions and harmony proxies, the spec
10813  // requires us to consider undefined as a kind of accessor, too:
10814  // var obj = {};
10815  // Object.defineProperty(obj, "foo", {get: undefined});
10816  // assertTrue("foo" in obj);
10817  bool IsJSAccessor(Object* obj) {
10818  return obj->IsSpecFunction() || obj->IsUndefined();
10819  }
10820 
10821  DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(AccessorPair);
10822 };
10823

11182 // Abstract base class for visiting, and optionally modifying, the
11183 // pointers contained in Objects. Used in GC and serialization/deserialization.
11184 class ObjectVisitor BASE_EMBEDDED {
11185  public:
11186  virtual ~ObjectVisitor() {}
11187 
11188  // Visits a contiguous arrays of pointers in the half-open range
11189  // [start, end). Any or all of the values may be modified on return.
11190  virtual void VisitPointers(Object** start, Object** end) = 0;
11191 
11192  // Handy shorthand for visiting a single pointer.
11193  virtual void VisitPointer(Object** p) { VisitPointers(p, p + 1); }
11194 
11195  // Visit weak next_code_link in Code object.
11196  virtual void VisitNextCodeLink(Object** p) { VisitPointers(p, p + 1); }
11197 
11198  // To allow lazy clearing of inline caches the visitor has
11199  // a rich interface for iterating over Code objects..
11200 
11201  // Visits a code target in the instruction stream.
11202  virtual void VisitCodeTarget(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11203 
11204  // Visits a code entry in a JS function.
11205  virtual void VisitCodeEntry(Address entry_address);
11206 
11207  // Visits a global property cell reference in the instruction stream.
11208  virtual void VisitCell(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11209 
11210  // Visits a runtime entry in the instruction stream.
11211  virtual void VisitRuntimeEntry(RelocInfo* rinfo) {}
11212 
11213  // Visits the resource of an ASCII or two-byte string.
11214  virtual void VisitExternalAsciiString(
11215  v8::String::ExternalAsciiStringResource** resource) {}
11216  virtual void VisitExternalTwoByteString(
11217  v8::String::ExternalStringResource** resource) {}
11218 
11219  // Visits a debug call target in the instruction stream.
11220  virtual void VisitDebugTarget(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11221 
11222  // Visits the byte sequence in a function's prologue that contains information
11223  // about the code's age.
11224  virtual void VisitCodeAgeSequence(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11225 
11226  // Visit pointer embedded into a code object.
11227  virtual void VisitEmbeddedPointer(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11228 
11229  // Visits an external reference embedded into a code object.
11230  virtual void VisitExternalReference(RelocInfo* rinfo);
11231 
11232  // Visits an external reference. The value may be modified on return.
11233  virtual void VisitExternalReference(Address* p) {}
11234 
11235  // Visits a handle that has an embedder-assigned class ID.
11236  virtual void VisitEmbedderReference(Object** p, uint16_t class_id) {}
11237 
11238  // Intended for serialization/deserialization checking: insert, or
11239  // check for the presence of, a tag at this position in the stream.
11240  // Also used for marking up GC roots in heap snapshots.
11241  virtual void Synchronize(VisitorSynchronization::SyncTag tag) {}
11242 };

11254 // BooleanBit is a helper class for setting and getting a bit in an
11255 // integer or Smi.
11256 class BooleanBit : public AllStatic {
11257  public:
11258  static inline bool get(Smi* smi, int bit_position) {
11259  return get(smi->value(), bit_position);
11260  }
11261 
11262  static inline bool get(int value, int bit_position) {
11263  return (value & (1 << bit_position)) != 0;
11264  }
11265 
11266  static inline Smi* set(Smi* smi, int bit_position, bool v) {
11267  return Smi::FromInt(set(smi->value(), bit_position, v));
11268  }
11269 
11270  static inline int set(int value, int bit_position, bool v) {
11271  if (v) {
11272  value |= (1 << bit_position);
11273  } else {
11274  value &= ~(1 << bit_position);
11275  }
11276  return value;
11277  }
11278 };
